===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|crien|crien|to cry out, shout, proclaim|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|crier|crier|to announce publicly, scream, shout|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|cridare|crÄ«dÄre|to cry out, shout, proclaim|lang=la}}, of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|frk}} *{{term||krÄ«tan|to cry, cry out, publish|lang=frk}}, {{etyl|got}} {{term|ğŒºğ‚ğŒ´ğŒ¹ğ„ğŒ´ğŒ½||tr=crÄ«ten, kreiten|to cry, scream, call out|lang=got}}, both from {{proto|Germanic|krÄ«tanan|to cry out, shout|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|greid-|to shout|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|criten|crÄ«ten||lang=osx}} ({{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|krijten|krijten||lang=nl}} "to cry"), {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|kriten|krÄ«ten|to cry, call out, shriek|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|krizen|krÄ«zen|to cry loudly, wail, groan|lang=gmh|tr={{etyl|de|-}} {{term|kreissen|lang=de}}}}. Compare also to {{etyl|oc|-}} {{term|cridar|cridar||lang=oc}}, {{etyl|it|-}} {{term|gridare|gridare||lang=it}}, {{etyl|osp|-}} {{term|cridar|cridar||lang=osp}} ({{etyl|es|-}} {{term|gritar|gritar||lang=es}}). Cognate with {{etyl|mga|-}} {{term|grith||a cry|lang=mga}}, {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|gryd||a scream|lang=cy}}.

{{rel-top|etymology note}}
Alternate etymology connects the {{etyl|ML.|-}} word to {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|queri||to complain|lang=la}} through the form {{term|quiritare||to wail, shriek|lang=la}}, though the phonetic and semantic developments are difficult to explain (''cridare'' meant "shout, yell, proclaim", not "complain, lament, wail"). Compare also Sanskrit ''cvas'' "to [[pant]]", "[[hiss]]", "[[sigh]]"; English ''[[quarrel]]'' a brawl, ''[[querulous]]''.

{{enm}} {{term|crien|crien||lang=enm}} displaced native [[Middle English]] ''[[galen#Middle English|galen]]'' "to cry out" (from [[Old English]] ''[[galan#Old English|galan]]''), [[Middle English]] ''[[greden#Middle English|greden]]'' "to cry out" (from [[Old English]] {{term|grÃ¦dan|grÇ£dan|sc=Latinx|lang=ang}}), [[Middle English]] ''[[yermen#Middle English|yermen]]'' "to bellow, mourn, lament" (from [[Old English]] ''[[gierman#Old English|Ä¡ierman]]''), [[Middle English]] ''[[hoen#Middle English|hooen, hoen]]'' "to cry out" (from Old Norse ''[[hoa#Old Norse|hÅa]]''), [[Middle English]] ''[[remen#Middle English|remen]]'' "to cry, shout" (from [[Old English]] ''[[hrieman#Old English|hrÄ«eman]]'', compare [[Old English]] ''[[hream#Old English|hrÄ“am]]'' "noise, outcry, lamentation, alarm"), [[Middle English]] ''[[gretan#Middle English|greten, graten]]'' "to weep, cry, lament" (from [[Old English]] {{term|grÃ¦tan|grÇ£tan|sc=Latinx|lang=ang}} and Old Norse ''[[grata#Old Norse|grÄta]]''). More at [[greet]], [[regret]].
